         <abstract>
            <p>A Markov triple is a set of three positive integers satisfying the diophantine equation (x&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + y&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; + z&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; = 3xyz). The maximum of the triple is called a Markov number. Although all Markov triples can be generated from the triple (1, 1, 1), it is not known whether it is possible to obtain (p, a&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;, b&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;) and (p, a&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, b&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;), where p is the same Markov number for both triples. All Markov numbers not exceeding 30 digits were computed without turning up a duplication, lending some credence to the conjecture that the Markov numbers are unique.</p>
          </abstract>
